A May shuttle began a test shift on experimental software in a parking sub-lot. The vehicle exited the sub-lot and rolled over a curb. The vehicle stopped at a stop sign at the exit of the main lot. As it proceeded to turn onto the main road, it rolled over another curb. Almost immediately after rolling the curb, the vehicle began to drift right in lane, rubbing the vehicle sidewall on a curb. The test driver intervened immediately, but not before the sidewall of the rear right tire was weakened. Later during the drive while under manual control, the sidewall fails, eventually leading to a low pressure indicator illuminating in the dash. It was discovered that the deployment of map files, which must remain compatible, was incomplete, leaving a mismatch in the system. This resulted in the vehicle having an incorrect estimate of where lanes are in the coordinates of our localization map, and as a result, the vehicle had an incorrect estimate of proximity to lane boundaries, resulting in curb strikes.

On JUN-2024, Volkswagen Group of America, Inc. ("VW") filed an Incident Report (NHTSA-provided Report ID-1420-7914- the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "SGO"). The subject vehicle referred to in the Report contains the Reporter's  software and hardware. Since the Reporter is also a Reporting Entity under the SGO, the Reporter hereby submits this report. In order to avoid duplications and additional CBI requests, this submission includes the publicly available information of the Report and incorporates the Report by reference. This submission is based on the information provided to the Reporter by VW. The Reporter currently believes that it has no independent knowledge of the information in this report.
From Volkswagen:
The subject vehicle (autonomous vehicle - AV) was proceeding through a parking garage while engaged in autonomous driving (AD) mode.  The AV detected an oncoming passenger vehicle (PV), made adjustments to its route by moving to the right, and slowed to a stop to provide additional space for the PV.  As the PV passed, it attempted to make a left-hand turn behind the AV, but the PV's driver side mirror scraped the rear driver's side LiDAR housing of the AV.  The passenger vehicle continued driving without stopping. After noticing the contact, the safety driver of the subject vehicle manually disengaged AD mode to assess the incident.  There were no reported injuries, airbag deployments, or tow-aways.  The damage to the subject vehicle was a scuff to the driver's side Short Range LiDAR trim cover.  VWGoA does not plan to investigate the incident any further as the facts and circumstances do not indicate any issue with the vehicle's performance.

On September [XXX], 2021 at 1:58 AM PDT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in Tempe, AZ was in a collision involving a passenger car in a parking lot at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stationary in a parking lot aisle, waiting to pick up passengers. A passenger vehicle on the left of the Waymo AV reversed out of a parking spot and the rear bumper on the driver's side of that vehicle made contact with the Waymo AV's driver's side rear passenger door. A Local Motors electric Olli shuttle (V1.0), VIN equipped with the Robotic Research autonomy kit (enabling autonomous steering, acceleration, deceleration, and braking (AutoDrive)), was proceeding forward in autonomous mode through a parking lot in Yellowstone National Park. A parked passenger vehicle began reversing into the path of the Olli without signaling or yielding the right of way to oncoming shuttle. The autonomy system detected the encroaching vehicle and commanded a braking event, which began deceleration of the Olli.  Though the Olli was nearly stopped by the time the of the accident, a collision still occurred, causing damage to the right rear of the passenger vehicle.  For reference this incident is under review with the Box-7 Team at NHTSA.
